INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'bbd7f127-0c6e-4a76-8583-93b1b739dc0d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Helm Image Values — Layers, Digests, and Copy-on-Write at Replica Scale$escape$,
  $escape$Every Helm chart deployment ultimately references a container image — a read-only stack of filesystem layers. Helm's canonical values.yaml pattern separates image.repository, image.tag, and image.pullPolicy deliberately: each controls how Kubernetes resolves and caches those layers on the node.

imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent tells the kubelet to skip the registry when image layers are already cached — critical for fast pod restarts and air-gapped clusters. Always forces a manifest digest check on every start, catching updated :latest tags at the cost of registry round-trips.

Prefer digest pinning over mutable tags in production charts. image.digest: sha256:abc123... produces an immutable layer reference. Override it with --set image.digest=sha256:... on helm upgrade and helm history will track the exact layer stack per revision — something a floating tag like :v1.2 can never guarantee.

The copy-on-write filesystem matters most when replicaCount is high. All 20 pods on a node share the same read-only image layers — only each pod's thin writable CoW layer differs. Helm's rolling update knobs, maxSurge and maxUnavailable in the deployment template, directly control how many new CoW layers Kubernetes provisions in parallel during an upgrade cycle.$escape$,
  $escape$# Pin by digest in values.yaml — tag left empty to avoid ambiguity
# image.repository: ghcr.io/myorg/api
# image.tag: ""
# image.digest: "sha256:a1b2c3..."
# image.pullPolicy: IfNotPresent

# Upgrade with new digest — immutable, fully tracked by helm history
helm upgrade my-app ./chart \
  --set image.digest=sha256:a1b2c3d4e5f67890abcdef1234567890abcdef12 \
  --set replicaCount=20

# Confirm all pods resolved to the same layer stack (CoW: one set per node)
kubectl get pods -l app.kubernetes.io/name=my-app \
  -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.spec.containers[0].image}{"\n"}{end}'$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
