INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '029caf87-25cb-4260-b56f-8e5890964a72',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Helm Deployments Are Faster When Your Dockerfile Isn't Lazy$escape$,
  $escape$Helm deployments live and die by image pull time and rollout stability. Optimizing your Dockerfile directly reduces `helm upgrade` rollout duration and prevents the silent failures that plague production releases.

Layer caching is your first lever: copy dependency manifests (`go.mod`, `package.json`, `requirements.txt`) before source files. Docker rebuilds only layers below the first changed layer — so a source-only change skips the expensive dependency install on every CI pipeline that feeds `helm upgrade`.

Multi-stage builds eliminate build toolchain from your runtime image. A Go binary built from `golang:1.22-alpine` drops to ~8MB in `distroless/static:nonroot` — roughly 30x smaller than the builder stage. Kubernetes nodes pull this image far faster, cutting time-to-Ready for pods during Helm rollouts with `--atomic`.

Pin images in Helm values by digest, not just tag — tags are mutable and cause `helm upgrade` to silently deploy different code across environments. Capturing the SHA256 digest post-build and passing it via `--set image.digest` makes your `helm history` a true, reproducible audit trail. Combine with `imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent` to leverage node-level layer cache on re-deploys.$escape$,
  $escape$# Build and capture immutable digest — never trust a mutable tag
docker build -t myregistry/api:v1.2.3 .
DIGEST=$(docker inspect --format='{{index .RepoDigests 0}}' myregistry/api:v1.2.3 | cut -d@ -f2)

# Helm upgrade pinned by digest for reproducible, auditable rollouts
helm upgrade my-app ./charts/my-app \
  --set image.repository=myregistry/api \
  --set image.tag=v1.2.3 \
  --set image.digest="${DIGEST}" \
  --set image.pullPolicy=IfNotPresent \
  --atomic \
  --timeout 5m$escape$,
