INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c1549a00-7b12-4bd1-9762-e2aa4147816d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Helm and Kubernetes Architecture — How helm install Touches the Control Plane$escape$,
  $escape$Every `helm install` or `helm upgrade` call goes exclusively through the kube-apiserver — Helm never talks to etcd, the scheduler, or kubelets directly. Helm 3 stores release state as Kubernetes Secrets (type `helm.sh/release.v1`) in the target namespace; those secrets are serialized, gzipped, and base64-encoded before the API server persists them to etcd. This means etcd is your release history's source of truth — not Helm's local cache.

On the worker node side, Helm only authors manifests. Once `helm install` POSTs resources to the API server, the controller manager reconciles them and the scheduler assigns pods to nodes. Helm's `--wait` flag polls the API server's watch stream until Deployments report `Available`, giving you a synchronization point without coupling Helm to any individual node.

If the API server is unreachable, every Helm command fails — even `helm list`, which reads release secrets from the cluster, not a local file. Understanding this flow matters when debugging: a failed `helm upgrade` with a partial rollout means etcd holds the new release Secret but the controller manager may still be reconciling worker-node pods.$escape$,
  $escape$# Inspect Helm release secrets stored in etcd (via API server)
kubectl get secrets -n my-namespace \
  -l owner=helm,status=deployed \
  -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.name}{"\n"}{end}'

# Decode a release secret to inspect the stored manifest
kubectl get secret sh.helm.release.v1.my-release.v3 \
  -n my-namespace \
  -o jsonpath='{.data.release}' \
  | base64 -d | base64 -d | gunzip | jq '.manifest'

# helm upgrade with API-server watch synchronization
helm upgrade my-release ./chart \
  --wait \
  --timeout 5m \
  --atomic$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
