INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2fe3fa86-506b-4b10-81ce-964d0c81d2ad',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Helm — Resource Requests vs Limits, QoS Classes, and Surviving OOMKill$escape$,
  $escape$Every Helm chart you deploy lands in one of three Kubernetes QoS classes based on how you configure resources in your values.yaml — and that class determines who dies first under node pressure.

BestEffort (no requests or limits set) gets evicted immediately. Burstable (requests < limits, or only one set) gets a middle seat. Guaranteed (requests == limits for both CPU and memory) is the last to go.

In your chart templates, always expose both fields via values so operators can tune per-environment. A common mistake: setting only limits without requests — Kubernetes defaults requests to the limit value, giving you Guaranteed class unintentionally in dev but Burstable in prod when someone overrides limits only.

For memory, OOMKill happens when a container exceeds its limit — no grace period, just SIGKILL. Set memory limits conservatively: use kubectl top pods after load testing, then add a 20–30% buffer. CPU throttling is recoverable; memory OOMKill is not. Use Helm's .Values pattern to enforce sane defaults while allowing per-release overrides via --set or a separate values file.$escape$,
  $escape$# values.yaml
resources:
  requests:
    cpu: "250m"
    memory: "256Mi"
  limits:
    cpu: "500m"
    memory: "512Mi"

---
# templates/deployment.yaml
containers:
  - name: {{ .Chart.Name }}
    resources:
      requests:
        cpu: {{ .Values.resources.requests.cpu | quote }}
        memory: {{ .Values.resources.requests.memory | quote }}
      limits:
        cpu: {{ .Values.resources.limits.cpu | quote }}
        memory: {{ .Values.resources.limits.memory | quote }}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
