INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b8da0118-c93b-44a2-808e-25510111a849',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Helm StatefulSets — Wiring PersistentVolumes and Storage Classes the Right Way$escape$,
  $escape$StatefulSets in Helm require `volumeClaimTemplates` — not `volumes` — to get stable, per-pod PVCs. Unlike Deployments, each StatefulSet pod gets its own PVC (e.g., `data-myapp-0`, `data-myapp-1`) that survives pod restarts and is never garbage-collected on `helm uninstall` by default. This is intentional: data outlives the release.

Parameterize the `storageClassName` through `values.yaml` so operators can swap between `standard`, `premium-ssd`, or cloud-native classes (`gp3`, `managed-premium`) without touching the template. Always expose `storage` size as a value too — resizing a bound PVC is painful and often requires manual intervention.

Critical Helm gotcha: `helm upgrade` cannot modify `volumeClaimTemplates` — it's an immutable field on the StatefulSet spec. Any change triggers a failed upgrade. The only safe path is delete-and-recreate, which means pre-upgrade PVC backup is your responsibility. Use `helm upgrade --force` only if data loss is acceptable. For production, treat storage config changes as migrations, not upgrades.$escape$,
  $escape$# values.yaml
storage:
  className: gp3
  size: 20Gi

# templates/statefulset.yaml
volumeClaimTemplates:
  - metadata:
      name: data
    spec:
      accessModes: ["ReadWriteOnce"]
      storageClassName: {{ .Values.storage.className }}
      resources:
        requests:
          storage: {{ .Values.storage.size }}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
