INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '19e718a0-3fc1-42d3-8f24-5231cb68d96c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Helm Rolling Updates & Rollbacks — Zero-Downtime Deployments Done Right$escape$,
  $escape$Helm delegates rolling updates to Kubernetes, but your chart values control the strategy. Set `strategy.type: RollingUpdate` with `maxUnavailable: 0` and `maxSurge: 1` in your deployment spec to guarantee zero downtime — no pod goes down until a healthy replacement is running. Helm's `--atomic` flag ties the release to this: if the rollout fails, it automatically rolls back and marks the release as failed.

Track history with `helm history <release>` — each `helm upgrade` increments the revision. Roll back instantly with `helm rollback <release> <revision>`, which re-applies the exact chart + values from that revision. Limit stored history via `--history-max` to avoid unbounded secrets accumulation in your cluster.

For canary-style deploys, combine Helm with separate releases (e.g. `myapp-canary`) or weight-based ingress annotations — Helm itself has no native traffic-splitting primitive. Always pair upgrades with `--timeout` and `--wait` so CI/CD pipelines block until pods are truly ready, not just scheduled.$escape$,
  $escape$# Upgrade with zero-downtime guarantees and auto-rollback
helm upgrade myapp ./chart \
  --atomic \
  --timeout 5m \
  --wait \
  --history-max 10 \
  -f values.prod.yaml

# Inspect revision history
helm history myapp

# Roll back to a specific revision
helm rollback myapp 3 --wait

# Corresponding deployment strategy in values.yaml:
# deployment:
#   strategy:
#     type: RollingUpdate
#     rollingUpdate:
#       maxUnavailable: 0
#       maxSurge: 1$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
