INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5907168d-f21c-4d26-a88d-98f20e0ccec9',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Helm Local Dev — Matching prod parity with kind and values overrides$escape$,
  $escape$Running `helm install` against a kind or minikube cluster exposes a common trap: your chart works locally but breaks in prod because you're shipping different values. The fix is layered values files — keep `values.yaml` as your prod baseline and override with `values.local.yaml` for local dev.

Use `helm install myapp ./chart -f values.yaml -f values.local.yaml` — Helm merges right-to-left, so the local file wins on conflicts. In `values.local.yaml`, disable PodDisruptionBudgets, set `replicaCount: 1`, swap in `NodePort` instead of `LoadBalancer`, and point image tags to `localhost:5000/myapp:dev` (your local registry). For kind, pre-load images with `kind load docker-image` to skip the registry entirely.

Crucially, never commit `values.local.yaml` — add it to `.gitignore`. Use `helm template myapp ./chart -f values.yaml -f values.local.yaml | kubectl diff -f -` to diff what would change before any apply. This gives you a reproducible local loop without drifting from the chart your CI deploys.$escape$,
  $escape$# values.local.yaml — never committed
replicaCount: 1
image:
  repository: localhost:5000/myapp
  tag: dev
  pullPolicy: Never
service:
  type: NodePort
podDisruptionBudget:
  enabled: false
resources:
  requests:
    cpu: 50m
    memory: 64Mi

# Load image into kind, then install with layered values
kind load docker-image localhost:5000/myapp:dev --name dev-cluster
helm upgrade --install myapp ./chart -f values.yaml -f values.local.yaml$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
