INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7dedad08-3cd4-4edd-9bd8-78a3842b61a9',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Helm — Wiring Full Observability into K8s Pods with One Chart$escape$,
  $escape$Helm's dependency system lets you co-deploy the full observability stack alongside your app in a single `helm install`. Define Loki, Prometheus, and Tempo as `dependencies` in `Chart.yaml`, then wire them to your pods via `values.yaml` — no manual kubectl piping required.

For logs, enable Loki's `promtail` scrape config to tail pod stdout/stderr by label. For metrics, annotate pods through your chart's `deployment.yaml` template with `prometheus.io/scrape: 'true'` and `prometheus.io/port`; Prometheus picks these up via its Helm-deployed `ServiceMonitor` CRD. For traces, inject the OpenTelemetry Collector as a sidecar using a Helm sub-chart, pointing `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` to Tempo via an env var in your `values.yaml`.

The real leverage: override per-environment in `values-prod.yaml` — crank up scrape intervals, toggle trace sampling rates, or disable Loki in local dev. One chart, three signal types, environment-aware without template duplication.$escape$,
  $escape$# Chart.yaml
dependencies:
  - name: loki-stack
    version: "2.10.2"
    repository: "https://grafana.github.io/helm-charts"
  - name: kube-prometheus-stack
    version: "58.1.3"
    repository: "https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts"
  - name: tempo
    version: "1.7.2"
    repository: "https://grafana.github.io/helm-charts"

# values.yaml
loki-stack:
  promtail:
    enabled: true

kube-prometheus-stack:
  prometheus:
    prometheusSpec:
      serviceMonitorSelectorNilUsesHelmValues: false

tempo:
  tempo:
    reportingEnabled: false

# In your deployment template
annotations:
  prometheus.io/scrape: "true"
  prometheus.io/port: "{{ .Values.app.metricsPort }}"$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
